##I spent three months planning a trip to Japan for the Spring Festival, which turned into a face mask shopping trip

This is Zheng Yi's first trip to Japan. Three months early, she and her siblings took an early annual leave, booked hotel tickets and planned a 15 day deep freedom tour of Japan during the Lunar New Year holiday.

On January 18th, flying 3,000 km, he set foot on Tokyo soil for the first time. She likes the cleanliness of Japanese streets, the different customs of Sensō-ji, Ginza and Omotesando, as well as the "rat" mascots that the Japanese have put in every corner -- a symbol of Japanese delight to Chinese tourists. At this time, Zheng's only worry is to eat too much sashimi, a little diarrhea.

But two days later, the whole world began to turn into magic.

In an interview with CCTV news on January 20, academician Zhong Nanshan delivered a shocking message: COVID-19 pneumonia exists from person to person. As of 24pm, 291 cases (270 cases in Hubei, 5 cases in Beijing, 14 cases in Guangdong and 2 cases in Shanghai) , 1 case in Japan, 2 cases in Thailand and 1 case in Korea were confirmed according to the National Health Commission.

Zheng's mobile phone has been crazy vibration, all kinds of news in countless wechat groups retweeted. Her family group immediately began to confirm how much alcohol was in the house, masks, each other do not go out, do not run around, do not gather.

On the other side of the phone, Zhengzhou, Japan, is getting nervous.

At a hotel in Tokyo, Japanese television was blaring news about pneumonia, saying that one hundred thousand Chinese had arrived.

Japan was originally one of the favorite overseas countries for Chinese people to visit during the Spring Festival. The number of Chinese tourists visiting Japan in February 2019(including during the Spring Festival) reached 650,000, according to the Japan entry and Exit Administration Office. But this Spring Festival in 2020, Chinese outbound travel was cut short.

On January 25, the China Association of Travel Agencies (CTA) announced that travel agencies and online travel companies across the country will suspend group tours and "air ticket + hotel" products from today. After January 27, all group tours and "machine + wine" services, including outbound tours, will be suspended.

Japan's tourism industry has been rocked by a drop in Chinese tourists. A number of Chinese tour groups have canceled trips to Japan before the end of March, and more than 400,000 Chinese tourists are expected to fail to travel as planned, the Japan Tourism Industry Association said Feb. 4.

It's a chain reaction. Japanese department stores suffered double-digit declines in duty-free sales over the Lunar New Year holiday, Japanese hotels saw their occupancy rates plummet and even Sika deer in Nara Park ran out of food.

But Cheng I, who was in Japan at the time, was unaware of such a change. The only thing she knew for sure was that their itinerary in Japan needed to be changed.

In Tokyo before the 20th, fewer than 10 percent of people wore masks at tourist sites, except for a small number of Japanese who wore masks on their vehicles for reasons of habit, Jung observed. After that, Japanese streets were covered in face masks for anything that looked Chinese.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Jan. 28, tourists at the site donned face masks. Source: Interviewees

At this time, the domestic social network has begun to spread the "mask price rise" , "can masks still ship? " , "ask a few to have masks to sell" of the comments.

Instead of enjoying the sights of Japan, they were interrupted by the Daily News of the outbreak on their mobile phones. Instead of planning a shopping trip, the three decided to go to a drugstore and buy some face masks to take home.

But what type of mask to buy in order to defend the new pneumonia virus, also let Zheng Yi three people confused for a long time. After a frantic search, the jargon only made it more confusing. Finally, they had rented a car to the Japanese driver for help, only to know to buy BFE, VFE, PFE three models of masks.

Since the 27th, they have been in "face mask shopping mode" . Every day from Kyoto to Ōsaka, whenever he passed a drugstore, he would go in and see if there were masks available. But it has not been easy, as Chinese tourists who have already arrived in Japan, along with locals, have emptied most of the stores'supply of masks.

Soon Japan began to limit the purchase of face masks. Zheng did not see any restrictions on buying masks at first, but as people rushed to buy them, some stores began limiting each person to two or three boxes. Despite this, masks continue to sell out.

Every time I see the pharmacy door posted "mask sold out" notice, Zheng Yi will worry about the back will not buy. Because of her large family, a few boxes may not be enough for the whole family. At the same time, there are many people who know that she is in Japan, asked can help to buy on behalf of the information swarmed to.

"I thought someone would ask me to buy cosmetics for them, but it turned out to be a mask, " Zheng quipped.

But there was nothing she could do. Zheng Yi would visit three or four drugstores every day, and within a few days he had run to ten stores. But I couldn't even buy enough face masks for my family.

"every one is out of stock, " Zheng told interface news.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 31st, Japanese pharmacies ran out of masks. Source: provided by respondents

Standing on the streets of ŌSAKA, Cheng I, unable to buy a mask, stopped passers-by to ask. It was a Hong Kong family that told Zheng that to buy masks, they had to go out early in the morning to look for them, and showed her a bag of masks they had grabbed and carried all day.

Zheng, who eventually found a store with the goods, joined the silent line of Chinese tourists, according to their account. She looked up and saw a few words written in Chinese at the door of the store, "go, Wuhan, go, China. ".

This is not the act of a single store. Sales of face masks across Japan surged after the outbreak, especially after Japan also reported confirmed cases. Although most of the people who flooded into pharmacies to buy face masks were Chinese, Japanese pharmacies did not take the opportunity to bid up prices, many stores have posted the words "go China" in front of their stores.

The masks, donated by Japan, are also a much-needed relief for China, where factories are closed for the Spring Festival holiday. Since January 25, when the first plane carrying a million face masks donated by the Japanese people arrived at the Chengdu Shuangliu International Airport, large quantities of epidemic prevention supplies have been donated from all parts of Japan and people from all walks of life have expressed their blessings in verse.

"When the snow melts in Liao River, the flowers bloom in the mountains; when we share the same air and branches, we look forward to the coming of spring. "

I will share my lower garments with you 

Eventually, all three of Zheng's siblings'suitcases and carry-on backpacks filled with masks whenever there was room. On Feb. 1, when Zheng was on her way home, the airport was very different from when she arrived. Everyone from Asia wore masks, and one European American even wore goggles.

And her war has only just begun.
